title: Optimal payoff under Bregman-Wasserstein divergence constraints

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We study optimal payoff choice for an expected utility maximizer under the constraint that their payoff is not allowed to deviate "too much" from a given benchmark. We solve this problem when the deviation is assessed via a Bregman-Wasserstein (BW) divergence, generated by a convex function $\phi$. Unlike the Wasserstein distance (i.e., when $\phi(x)=x^{2}$ ). The inherent asymmetry of the BW divergence makes it possible to penalize positive deviations different than negative ones. As a main contribution, we provide the optimal payoff in this setting. Numerical examples illustrate that the choice of $\phi$ allow to better align the payoff choice with the objectives of investors.


Key words. Portfolio choice, Preferences, Expected Utility, Hoeffding-Fréchet bounds, Bregman Divergence, Wasserstein distance.

1. Introduction. A standard assumption in the literature on optimal payoff choice is that investors' preferences can be described by the expected utility theory (EUT) of von Neumann and Morgenstern (1947). This approach has however faced significant criticisms and researchers have explored optimal payoff choices under alternative decision theories. Notable are the dual theory of Yaari (1987), the rank-dependent expected utility (RDEUT) approach of Quiggin (1993), and several behavioural approaches, including the SP/A theory of Lopes (1987) and Shefrin and Statman (2000), and the cumulative prospect theory (CPT) of Tversky and Kahneman (1992). Despite extensive research within these alternative frameworks ${ }^{1}$, none prove superior to EUT for the problem of optimal portfolio choice. For instance, under Yaari's dual theory, optimal payoffs often materialize as binary (digital) or trinary options, which are infrequently practical since investors rarely opt for such payoffs. In addition, Bernard et al. (2015a) demonstrate that the optimal payoff of an investor with law-invariant increasing preferences can always be rationalized via a concave utility function, and their optimal payoff obtained by maximizing the corresponding expected utility.

In real-world investment contexts, investors commonly encounter constraints on fund allocation. For instance, shareholders of an investment company often seek a balance between risk and return, whereas a supervisory authority of a pension fund prioritizes the fund's ability to meet participant obligations. Additionally, asset managers frequently establish a benchmark when engaging with clients, striving to outperform it without significant deviation. Moreover, within Markowitz's seminal mean-variance framework, additional constraints are typically imposed on the composition of buy-and-hold portfolios to ensure "reasonable" allocations. As a consequence, various studies have delved into optimal payoff selection under diverse con-

For instance, Basak and Shapiro (2001) derive the optimal payoff for an EUT maximizer under the constraint of maintaining the Value-at-Risk (VaR) within acceptable limits. Other studies in this realm include Wei (2021), Cuoco et al. (2008), and Chen et al. (2024).

In this paper, we examine the optimal choices for an EUT investor who is concerned about the deviation of their payoff from a specified benchmark. Related problems has been investigated in Pesenti and Jaimungal (2023) and Jaimungal et al. (2022). The former considers Yaari investors and used (among other constraints) the 2-Wasserstein distance to measure divergence while the latter focuses on RDEUT and the $p$-Wasserstein distance. The $p$-Wasserstein distance arises as the solution to the Monge-Kantorovich optimal transport (OT) problem with the symmetric cost function $c\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)=\left|z_{1}-z_{2}\right|^{p}$. Thus positive deviations (gains) from a benchmark are penalised to the same extent as negative ones (losses) ${ }^{2}$. In optimal payoff choice, however, asymmetry may be desired. Specifically, since the fundamental work of Tversky and Kahneman (1992), it is well accepted that individuals tend to feel the pain of losses more acutely than the pleasure from equivalent gains. We contribute to the literature by studying the optimal payoff choice when the investor assigns asymmetric penalties for gains versus losses with respect to an entire reference distribution - a benchmark - rather than a specific reference point.

To the best of our knowledge, such asymmetry to a benchmark distribution has not yet been explored. To quantify dissimilarities between gains and losses we use the so-called Bregman-Wasserstein (BW) divergence which was introduced in the OT literature by Carlier and Jimenez (2007) and extensively studied in Rankin and Wong (2023). A BW divergence is the minimiser of the Monge-Kantorovich OT problem where the cost function is a Bregman divergence. The BW divergence, which is generated by a convex function $\phi$, is thus an asymmetric generalisation of the 2-Wasserstein distance, which is recovered with $\phi(x)=x^{2}$.

We consider a static setting, where admissible payoffs are non-negative measurable functions of a risky asset's terminal value, i.e., we deal with path-independent payoffs (see also Rüschendorf and Vanduffel (2020)). Clearly an optimal payoff in the static setting might be surpassed if dynamic trading is permitted, but this outperformance is only apparent if transactions do not bear a cost. In fact, if each transaction has a minimum cost, continuous trading leads to instantaneous bankruptcy and thus is not feasible. Allowing for discrete intermediate trading could mitigate this issue, but it presents major mathematical challenges ${ }^{3}$. The class of path-independent payoffs is extensive in that any distribution function of terminal wealth can be attained and - under technical conditions - the path-independent payoff can be replicated by trading at series of suitable calls and puts ${ }^{4}$ (see Breeden and Litzenberger (1978)).

The paper is structured as follows. Section 2 provides the investors problem description and Section 3 provides our main result, that is the optimal investment strategy. Section 4 discusses examples and Section 5 concludes.

# 2. Problem Formulation. 

2.1. Financial Market. There are two assets available in the market, a risk-free asset with current value $B_{0}>0$ and value $B_{T}=B_{0} e^{r T}$ at terminal time $T>0$, where $r>0$ is the risk-free interest rate, and a risky asset with current value $S_{0}>0$ and value at time $T$ that is described by the random variable $S_{T}: \Omega \rightarrow[0, \infty)$. We operate within the probability space $(\Omega, \mathcal{F}, \mathbb{P})$, in which $\mathcal{F}=\sigma\left(S_{T}\right)$ denotes the $\sigma$-algebra generated by $S_{T}$ and $\mathbb{P}$ is a probability measure, which may be an objective statistical measure derived from historical data or a subjective measure chosen by the investor based on personal beliefs and preferences.

We consider an investor who aims to acquire at $t=0$ a non-negative payoff $X_{T}$ that is a measurable function of the risky asset's terminal value. Furthermore, $X_{T}$ must be affordable given the investor's initial budget $x_{0}>0$, meaning $X_{T}$ belongs to the set $\mathcal{X}\left(x_{0}\right)$ given by

$$
\mathcal{X}\left(x_{0}\right):=\left\{X_{T}=g\left(S_{T}\right) \mid g \text { non-negative, measurable, and } c\left(X_{T}\right) \leq x_{0}\right\}
$$

where $c\left(X_{T}\right)$ denotes the cost of $X_{T}$. We assume that a pricing measure $\mathbb{Q}$ exists and that the cost $c\left(X_{T}\right)$ of $X_{T}$ is given by $c\left(X_{T}\right):=\mathbb{E}_{\mathbb{Q}}\left[e^{-r T} X_{T}\right]$, where $\mathbb{E}_{\mathbb{Q}}[\cdot]$ denotes the expected value under $\mathbb{Q}$. Equivalently, the cost $c\left(X_{T}\right)$ can be written as

$$
c\left(X_{T}\right)=\mathbb{E}_{\mathbb{P}}\left[\varphi_{T} X_{T}\right]
$$

where $\varphi_{T}:=e^{-r T} \frac{\mathrm{~d} \mathbb{Q}}{\mathrm{~d} t}$ is the state price density. For simplicity, we write $\mathbb{E}[\cdot]:=\mathbb{E}_{\mathbb{P}}[\cdot]$, when considering the expected value under $\mathbb{P}$.

Remark 2.1. If call options $c_{K}:=\max \left\{S_{T}-K, 0\right\}$ are traded for all exercise prices $K \geq 0$, then the pricing measure $\mathbb{Q}$ is uniquely determined by these call prices, see e.g., Breeden and Litzenberger (1978), Ross (1976), and Nachman (1988).

In the sequel, all cumulative distribution functions (cdfs) are taken with respect to $\mathbb{P}$. For a given cdf $F$, we denote its (left-continuous) quantile function ${ }^{5}$ by $\bar{F}$ and for a random variable $Y$, we write $F_{Y}$ and $\bar{F}_{Y}$ for its cdf and quantile function, respectively. Furthermore, we assume that the state-price density $\varphi_{T}$ is continuously distributed, satisfies $0<\varphi_{T}<+\infty$ $\mathbb{P}$-a.s, and that $\lim _{u \downarrow 0} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(u)=0$.

As we work with non-negative random variables, we define by $\mathcal{Q}$ the set of quantile functions corresponding to non-negative random variables. That is

$$
\mathcal{Q}:=\{\bar{G}:(0,1) \rightarrow[0, \infty) \mid \bar{G} \text { is non-decreasing and left-continuous }\}
$$

2.2. Expected Utility Preferences. The investor employs a utility function $u(\cdot)$ to attach a value $u(x)$ to each payoff outcome $x$ of $X_{T}$ and evaluates $X_{T}$ by its expected utility $\mathbb{E}\left[u\left(X_{T}\right)\right]$. Throughout, we assume that the utility function $u:[0, \infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ satisfies the following properties:

[^0]:    ${ }^{5}$ The left-continuous quantile function of a cdf $F$ is defined as $\bar{F}(u)=\inf \{y \in \mathbb{R} \mid F(y) \geq u\}, 0<u<1$.

i) $u$ is twice continuously differentiable,
ii) $u$ is strictly increasing and strictly concave, i. e. $u^{\prime}(x)>0$ and $u^{\prime \prime}(x)<0$ for all $x \in[0, \infty)$, and
iii) $u$ satisfies the Inada-conditions, i. e.,

$$
\lim _{x \rightarrow 0} u^{\prime}(x)=\infty \quad \text { and } \quad \lim _{x \rightarrow \infty} u^{\prime}(x)=0
$$

The investor is thus risk averse and moreover the inverse marginal utility function $I:=$ $\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}:[0, \infty) \rightarrow[0, \infty)$ exists and is strictly decreasing and continuously differentiable.
2.3. Bregman-Wasserstein Uncertainty. The investor aims to control the divergence from their payoff to a given benchmark. To formalise this we utilise the notion of BregmanWasserstein divergence, for which we first recall the Bregman divergence.

Definition 2.2 (Bregman divergence). Let $\phi: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex and continuously differentiable function, called a Bregman generator. Then, the Bregman divergence with generator $\phi$ is defined as

$$
B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right):=\phi\left(z_{1}\right)-\phi\left(z_{2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(z_{2}\right)\left(z_{1}-z_{2}\right), \quad z_{1}, z_{2} \in \mathbb{R}
$$

where $\phi^{\prime}(z):=\frac{d}{d z} \phi(z)$ denotes the derivative of $\phi$.
As we work with non-negative random variables, we typically consider Bregman generators $\phi:[0, \infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$. Note that for the choice $\phi(x)=x^{2}$, it holds that $B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)=\left(z_{1}-z_{2}\right)^{2}$, i.e., we obtain the squared Euclidean distance. In general, however, the Bregman divergence lacks symmetry (and thus is not a distance). This asymmetry is of great interest in that it makes it possible to penalize positive deviations differently to negative one. Figure 1 illustrates the Bregman divergence for $\phi_{1}(x)=x^{2}$ (blue lines) and $\phi_{2}(x)=x \ln x, x>0$ (red lines). By symmetry it holds that $B_{\phi_{1}}(1.5,0.8)=0.49=B_{\phi_{1}}(0.8,1.5)$, while for $\phi_{2}(x)=x \ln x$, we have $B_{\phi_{2}}(1.5,0.8)=0.2429>0.1971=B_{\phi_{2}}(0.8,1.5)$.

With the Bregman divergence, we can define a divergence on the space of cdfs as follows. Let $\Pi\left(F_{1}, F_{2}\right)$ denote the set of all bivariate cdfs with marginal cdfs $F_{1}$ and $F_{2}$, respectively. Pesenti and Vanduffel (2024) investigate the Monge-Kantorovich optimal transport problem

$$
\mathscr{B}\left[F_{1}, F_{2}\right]:=\inf _{\pi \in \Pi\left(F_{1}, F_{2}\right)}\left\{\int_{\mathbb{R}^{2}} c\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right) \pi\left(\mathrm{d} z_{1}, \mathrm{~d} z_{2}\right)\right\}
$$

using as cost function $c\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)$ the Bregman divergence $B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)$ and show that the infimum is attained for the comonotonic coupling, i.e., by $\left(\bar{F}_{1}(U), \bar{F}_{2}(U)\right)$, for any $U \sim U(0,1)$. As a consequence, the so-called Bregman-Wasserstein (BW) divergence from $F_{1}$ to $F_{2}$ has representation

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left[F_{1}, F_{2}\right] & =\int_{0}^{1} B_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t), \bar{F}_{2}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& =\int_{0}^{1}\left(\phi\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t)\right)-\phi\left(\bar{F}_{2}(t)\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{2}(t)\right)\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t)-\bar{F}_{2}(t)\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the BW divergence only depends on the marginal cdfs, we write $\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left[F_{1}, F_{2}\right]=\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2}\right)$ and use square brackets for cdfs and round brackets for quantile functions.
2.4. Investor's Optimization Problem. The investor aims to maximize their expected utility under the constraint that their terminal wealth does not diverge too much from the terminal wealth arising from a benchmark (reference) portfolio. Thus, we study the following EUT distance constrained optimization problem:
(P)

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\max & \mathbb{E}\left[u\left(X_{T}\right)\right] \\
c\left(X_{T}\right) \leq x_{0} & \\
\bar{F}_{X_{T}} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}
\end{array}\right.
$$

where $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}$ is the set of quantile functions that have a BW divergence of at most $\varepsilon>0$ to the quantile function of the benchmark's terminal wealth $\bar{F}_{b}$, i.e.,

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}:=\left\{\bar{G} \mid \bar{G} \in \mathcal{Q} \quad \text { and } \quad \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{G}, \bar{F}_{b}\right) \leq \varepsilon\right\}
$$

The value of $\varepsilon>0$ is chosen by the investor and we refer to it as the tolerance level. To solve problem (P), we first reduce the set containing all payoffs $X_{T}$ to the subset of payoffs that are anti-monotonic ${ }^{6}$ to the state price density $\varphi_{T}$. To see this, assume that some payoff $X_{T}$ distributed with $F$ solves the EUT optimal payoff selection problem (P) and is

not anti-monotonic to the state price density $\varphi_{T}$. We can then obtain a payoff $\hat{X}_{T}$ that has the same cdf $F$ and is strictly cheaper. Indeed, $\hat{X}_{T}:=\hat{F}\left(1-F_{\varphi_{T}}\left(\varphi_{T}\right)\right)$ has distribution $F$, thus the same expected utility, and satisfies $c\left(\hat{X}_{T}\right)<c\left(X_{T}\right)$ by the Hoeffding-Fréchet bounds. This reasoning was first established in Dybvig (1988) and we refer to Rüschendorf and Vanduffel (2020) and many of the references therein for more detail. As a consequence, the optimal portfolio selection problem reduces to an optimization problem on real functions under monotonicity constraints (quantile functions).

Theorem 2.3 (Anti-monotonicity of solution). If the EUT optimization problem (P) has a solution, then there exists a solution $\hat{X}_{T}$ that is anti-monotonic with $\varphi_{T}$.

Payoffs that are anti-monotonic with the state price density $\varphi_{T}$ are called cost-efficient, see e.g., Bernard et al. (2014).

Next, we define the set of quantile functions that have a BW-distance to the reference cdf of at most $\varepsilon$ and whose corresponding cost-efficient payoff cost no more than $x_{0}$. Specifically,

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right):=\left\{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q} \mid \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right) \leq \varepsilon \text { and } \mathfrak{c}(\check{G}) \leq x_{0}\right\} \subseteq \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}
$$

where $\mathfrak{c}(\check{G}):=\int_{0}^{1} \check{G}(t) \check{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t$. The following result is now classical in the literature on portfolio choice and we omit its proof. ${ }^{7}$

Theorem 2.4 (Quantile reformulation). If $\check{F}$ is a solution to the optimization problem $(\check{P})$

$$
\max _{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)} \int_{0}^{1} u(\check{G}(t)) \mathrm{d} t
$$

then $\hat{X}_{T}=\check{F}\left(1-F_{\varphi_{T}}\left(\varphi_{T}\right)\right)$ solves problem $(\mathrm{P})$.
Solving the EUT optimal payoff choice problem under a BW divergence constraint thus involves addressing an optimization problem concerning functions under monotonicity constraints. In other words, it entails finding a suitable quantile function.
3. Optimal Payoff. In this section we solve the EUT optimisation problem $(\check{P})$. For this we first establish that problem $(\check{P})$ is well-defined and that there exists a unique solution.
3.1. Existence and Uniqueness. To obtain existence and uniqueness of the optimal payoff, we first establish that the constraint set is closed.

Lemma 3.1. The constraint set $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ is closed.
Proof. Recall that $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)=\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon} \cap\left\{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q} \mid \mathfrak{c}(\check{G}) \leq x_{0}\right\}$. Since the intersection of closed sets is closed, we only need to prove that both sets are closed. To see that $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}$ is closed, consider a sequence $\left\{\check{G}_{n}\right\} \in \mathcal{Q}$ whose limit

$$
\check{G}(t):=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \check{G}_{n}(t) \quad t \in(0,1)
$$

belongs to $\mathcal{Q}$, i.e., $\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}$. Then, by continuity of Bregman divergence, we have

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{n}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right)=B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right), \quad \text { for all } \quad t \in(0,1)
$$

Note that $B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{n}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right)$ is non-negative, applying Fatou's Lemma, we obtain

$$
\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right)=\int_{0}^{1} B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t \leq \liminf _{n \rightarrow \infty} \int_{0}^{1} B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{n}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t
$$

Thus, we conclude that $\check{G} \mapsto \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right)$ is lower semi-continuous. As the $\varepsilon$-sublevel set of a lower semi-continuous function is a closed set, see Theorem 7.1.1. in Kurdila and Zabarankin (2006), it holds that $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}$ is closed. To see that the latter set is closed, note that $\mathfrak{c}(\check{G})$ is a linear function of $\check{G}$, thus $\left\{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q} \mid \mathfrak{c}(\check{G}) \leq x_{0}\right\}$ is closed. Hence $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ is closed.

We require the constraint set to be non-empty and the existence of a quantile function with BW divergence strictly smaller than $\varepsilon$, stated in the following assumption.

Assumption 3.1. There exists a $\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ with $\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right)<\varepsilon$.
This assumption aligns with the Slater condition (Definition A.3). Given that $\mathfrak{c}(\check{G})$ is affine in $\check{G}$, it is sufficient to assume the existence of a $\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ that satisfies the BW constraint. This assumption is non-restrictive and is for example fulfilled if the benchmark's terminal wealth satisfies the budget constraint.

Theorem 3.2 (Existence and uniqueness). Let Assumption 3.1 be satisfied. Then there exists a unique solution, denoted by $\check{F}^{*}$, of Problem ( $\check{P}$ ). Moreover, at least one of the constraints, i.e., either the budget constraint or the BW constraint, is binding for $\check{F}^{*}$.

Proof. The proof is broken into three parts. First, we show that the constraint set $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ is convex. Second, we prove existence and uniqueness of the solution, and finally, we show that at least one constraints is binding.

Part 1. Convexity of constraint set. Take $\check{G}_{1}, \check{G}_{2} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ and define the convex combination $\check{G}_{\omega}:=\omega \check{G}_{1}+(1-\omega) \check{G}_{2}$ for $\omega \in[0,1]$. Clearly, $\int_{0}^{1} \check{G}_{\omega}(t) \check{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t \leq x_{0}$. Furthermore, as the Bregman divergence is convex in its first argument, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{\omega}, \check{F}_{b}\right) & =\int_{0}^{1} B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{\omega}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& \leq \omega \int_{0}^{1} B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{1}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t+(1-\omega) \int_{0}^{1} B_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{2}(t), \check{F}_{b}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& =\omega \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{1}, \check{F}_{b}\right)+(1-\omega) \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}_{2}, \check{F}_{b}\right) \\
& \leq \varepsilon
\end{aligned}
$$

where the last inequality follows since $\check{G}_{1}, \check{G}_{2} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$. Hence $\check{G}_{\omega} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ and $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ is a convex set.

Part 2. Existence and uniqueness. As $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ is convex, closed (by Lemma 3.1), and nonempty (by Assumption 3.1), and $u(\cdot)$ is strictly concave, the existence of a solution to problem $(\check{P})$ follows as an application of Theorem 2.8 in Ghossoub and Zhu (2023). Uniqueness follows from strict concavity of the utility function.

Part 3. At least one of the constraints is binding. Assume that the optimal quantile function $\bar{F}$ is in the interior of $\mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$, i.e., $\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)=\varepsilon^{\prime}<\varepsilon$ and $\mathfrak{c}(\bar{F})=x_{0}^{\prime}<x_{0}$. Next, define the quantile function $\bar{F}_{c}(t):=\bar{F}(t)+c$ for $c>0$, then we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{c}, \bar{F}_{b}\right) & =\int_{0}^{1}\left(\phi(\bar{F}(t)+c)-\phi\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\left(\bar{F}(t)+c-\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& =\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)+\int_{0}^{1}\left(\phi(\bar{F}(t)+c)-\phi(\bar{F}(t))-c \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& =\varepsilon^{\prime}+\int_{0}^{1}\left(\phi(\bar{F}(t)+c)-\phi(\bar{F}(t))-c \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t
\end{aligned}
$$

and

$$
\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{c}\right)=\mathfrak{c}(\bar{F})+c \int_{0}^{1} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t=x_{0}^{\prime}+c \int_{0}^{1} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t
$$

Note that we have $\phi(\bar{F}(t)+c)-\phi(\bar{F}(t))-c \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right) \geq 0$, by convexity of $\phi(\cdot)$, and that $\int_{0}^{1} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t>0$. Furthermore

$$
\lim _{c \rightarrow 0} \int_{0}^{1}\left(\phi(\bar{F}(t)+c)-\phi(\bar{F}(t))-c \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t=\lim _{c \rightarrow 0} c \int_{0}^{1} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t=0
$$

Since for each $c>0$ the above intervals are non-negative and by continuity with respect to $c$, there exists a $\tilde{c}>0$ such that $\varepsilon^{\prime}<\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{\tilde{c}}, \bar{F}_{b}\right) \leq \varepsilon$ and $c^{\prime}<\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{\tilde{c}}\right) \leq x_{0}$, which implies that $\bar{F}_{\tilde{c}}(t) \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$. Moreover, it holds that $\int_{0}^{1} u\left(\bar{F}_{\tilde{c}}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t>\int_{0}^{1} u(\bar{F}(t)) \mathrm{d} t$, which contradicts optimality of $\bar{F}$. Therefore, at least one of the constraints is binding.
3.2. Optimal Quantile Function. We resort to convex optimization theory to solve problem $(\bar{P})$. To this end, we assume in this section that Assumption 3.1 is satisfied and rewrite problem $(\bar{P})$ as follows:

$$
\inf _{\bar{G} \in \mathcal{Q}}\left\{\int_{0}^{1}-u(\bar{G}(t)) \mathrm{d} t \mid \mathfrak{c}(\bar{G})-x_{0} \leq 0, \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{G}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)-\varepsilon \leq 0\right\}
$$

As a direct consequence of Assumption 3.1, problem (3.1) satisfies the Slater condition (see Definition A.3). This guarantees that the regularity properties outlined in Theorem A. 1 are satisfied. Hence, if $\bar{G}^{*}$ is a solution to problem (3.1), Theorem A. 1 ensures the existence of $\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*} \geq 0$ such that

$$
-\int_{0}^{1} u\left(\bar{G}^{*}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t \leq-\int_{0}^{1} u(\bar{G}(t)) \mathrm{d} t+\lambda^{*}\left(\mathfrak{c}(\bar{G})-x_{0}\right)+\mu^{*}\left(\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{G}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)-\varepsilon\right)
$$

for all $\bar{G} \in \mathcal{Q}$. Additionally, by Theorem A.1, case 3., we have

$$
\lambda^{*}\left(\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{G}^{*}\right)-x_{0}\right)=0 \quad \text { and } \quad \mu^{*}\left(\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{G}^{*}, \bar{F}\right)-\varepsilon\right)=0
$$

Adding these terms to the left-hand side of (3.2) and cancelling the $x_{0}$ and $\varepsilon$ terms yields:

$$
\int_{0}^{1}-u\left(\check{G}^{*}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t+\lambda^{*} \mathfrak{c}\left(\check{G}^{*}\right)+\mu^{*} \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}^{*}, \check{F}_{b}\right) \leq \int_{0}^{1}-u(\check{G}(t)) \mathrm{d} t+\lambda^{*} \mathfrak{c}(\check{G})+\mu^{*} \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right)
$$

for all $\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}$. Therefore, $\check{G}^{*}$ must also be a solution to the problem

$$
\underset{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}}{\arg \min }\left\{\int_{0}^{1}-u(\check{G}(t)) \mathrm{d} t+\lambda^{*} \mathfrak{c}(\check{G})+\mu^{*} \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right)\right\}
$$

Next, Theorem A. 4 shows that any solution of (3.4) that satisfies the slackness conditions (3.3), is also optimal for problem (3.2). Thus, for arbitrary given multipliers $\lambda, \mu \geq 0$, we next solve

$$
\underset{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}}{\arg \min }\left\{\int_{0}^{1}-u(\check{G}(t)) \mathrm{d} t+\lambda \mathfrak{c}(\check{G})+\mu \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\check{G}, \check{F}_{b}\right)\right\}
$$

$$
=\underset{\check{G} \in \mathcal{Q}}{\arg \min }\left\{\int_{0}^{1}-u(\check{G}(t))+\lambda \check{G}(t) \check{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu\left(\phi(\check{G}(t))-\phi^{\prime}\left(\check{F}_{b}(t)\right) \check{G}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t\right\}
$$

Fix a value of $t \in(0,1)$, and consider the integrand of problem (3.5) as a function of $y \in$ $[0,+\infty)$, defined as

$$
h_{t}(y):=m(y)+\lambda y \check{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)-\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\check{F}_{b}(t)\right) y
$$

where we set $m(y):=-u(y)+\mu \phi(y)$. Then, we consider the pointwise optimiser of $h_{t}(\cdot)$, that is for each $t \in(0,1)$ we solve

$$
\underset{y \in[0, \infty)}{\arg \min } h_{t}(y)
$$

As a solution to (3.7) minimizes the integral in (3.5) pointwise, it is a potential solution to problem (3.5), if the solution to (3.7) is a quantile function, i.e., non-decreasing and leftcontinuous. In the following, we first solve (3.7) and second verify that its solution is indeed a quantile function.

Proposition 3.3. For $\lambda, \mu \geq 0$ and for all $t \in(0,1)$, let

$$
\check{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t):=\inf \left\{y \geq 0 \mid \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y) \geq 0\right\}
$$

where by convention we set $\inf \emptyset:=+\infty$. Then

$$
\check{G}_{\lambda, \mu}=\underset{H:(0,1) \rightarrow[0, \infty)}{\arg \min } \int_{0}^{1}-u(H(t)) \mathrm{d} t+\lambda \mathfrak{c}(H)+\mu \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(H, \check{F}_{b}\right)
$$

Proof. We prove that for each $t \in(0,1), \check{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)$ is the solution to (3.7). Then, as $\check{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)$ minimises $h_{t}(y)$ pointwise, it follows that $\check{G}_{\lambda, \mu}$ is a solution to (3.9). First, as $u(\cdot)$ is strictly

concave and $\phi$ is convex, it holds that $h_{t}(y)$ is strictly convex in $y$. Moreover, $h_{t}(y)$ is differentiable in $y$ and $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y)$ is continuous and strictly increasing in $y$. Thus, if there exist $\hat{y} \in[0, \infty)$ such that $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(\hat{y})=0$, then $h_{t}(\hat{y})$ is the unique minimum of $h_{t}(\cdot)$ over $[0, \infty)$. Next, we show that either such a $\hat{y}$ exists or the argmin is equal to $+\infty$. For this, using the Inada-conditions, we obtain

$$
\lim _{y \rightarrow 0} \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y)=\lim _{y \rightarrow 0}-u^{\prime}(y)+\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu\left(\phi^{\prime}(y)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right)<0
$$

since by convexity of $\phi$, it holds that $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0} \phi^{\prime}(y)<+\infty$. Indeed if $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0} \phi^{\prime}(y)=+\infty$, then $\phi^{\prime}(y)=+\infty$ for all $y \geq 0$, since $\phi^{\prime}$ is non-decreasing. From the above inequality, we obtain that for each $t \in(0,1)$, the integrand $h_{t}(y)$ is decreasing at $y=0$, which implies that the argmin cannot be equal to zero for all $t \in(0,1)$.

Next, we consider the case when $\lim _{y \rightarrow+\infty} \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y)<0$, that is $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y)$ does not cross zero. Since $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y)<0$ for all $y$, we obtain that $h_{t}(y)$ attains its minimum at $+\infty$. Hence, we conclude $h_{t}(y)$ is minimized by (3.8).

The next proposition establishes that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}$ is a quantile function.
Proposition 3.4. For all $\lambda, \mu \geq 0, \bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(\cdot)$ is non-decreasing and left-continuous.
Proof. We first show non-decreasingness and then left-continuity.
Part 1. Non-decreasingness. First, we show that if there exists a $t_{1} \in(0,1)$ such that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)=+\infty$, then $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right)=+\infty$ for all $t_{2} \geq t_{1}$. From the proof of Proposition 3.3, we know that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)=+\infty$ is equivalent to

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t_{1}}(y)=m^{\prime}(y)+\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{1}\right)-\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{1}\right)\right)<0
$$

for all $y \in[0, \infty)$. Since $\bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)$ is decreasing and $\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)$ is non-decreasing with respect to $t$, we also obtain that

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t_{2}}(y)=m^{\prime}(y)+\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{2}\right)-\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{2}\right)\right)<0
$$

for all $y \in[0, \infty)$, and thus $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right)=+\infty$. Thus, we conclude that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)=+\infty$, implies that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right)=+\infty$ for all $t_{2} \geq t_{1}$.

Next, we verify that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)$ is non-decreasing within the set $\left\{t \in(0,1) \mid \bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)<+\infty\right\}$. For $t_{1}<t_{2}$ in that set, we have by continuity of $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}(y)$ that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t_{1}}(y)=m^{\prime}\left(\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)\right)+\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{1}\right)-\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{1}\right)\right)=0, \quad \text { and } \\
& \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t_{2}}(y)=m^{\prime}\left(\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right)\right)+\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{2}\right)-\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{2}\right)\right)=0
\end{aligned}
$$

Subtracting the two equations and rearranging, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
m^{\prime}\left(\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right)\right)-m^{\prime}\left(\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)\right)=- & \lambda\left(\bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{2}\right)-\bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{1}\right)\right) \\
& +\mu\left(\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{2}\right)\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{1}\right)\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that the right hand side of (3.10) is non-negative by the monotonicity of the quantile functions $\bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(\cdot)$ and $\bar{F}_{b}(\cdot)$. Thus

$$
m^{\prime}\left(\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right)\right)-m^{\prime}\left(\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)\right) \geq 0
$$

which implies that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{2}\right) \geq \bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{1}\right)$, since $m^{\prime}(\cdot)$ is non-decreasing. Hence, $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}$ is indeed non-decreasing.

Part 2. Left-continuity. We show that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(\cdot)$ is left-continuous at the point $t \in\{s \in$ $(0,1) \mid \bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(s)<+\infty\}$. Let $\left\{t_{n}\right\}_{n \in \mathbb{N}}$ be an non-decreasing sequence, $t_{n} \leq t_{n+1}$ for all $n \in \mathbb{N}$, that satisfies $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} t_{n}=t$. Next, we denote $g(n):=\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}\left(t_{n}\right), n \in \mathbb{N}$, and $g(\infty):=$ $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)$. To obtain left-continuity we need to show that $g:=\lim _{n \rightarrow+\infty} g(n)=g(\infty)$. By non-decreasingness of the sequence $\left\{t_{n}\right\}_{n \in \mathbb{N}}$ and of $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(\cdot)$, it holds that $g(n) \leq g(\infty)$ for all $n \in \mathbb{N}$. Thus, by to the Monotone Convergence Theorem

$$
g=\lim _{n \rightarrow+\infty} g(n) \leq g(\infty)
$$

As the sequence $g(\cdot)$ is non-decreasing, have that $g(n) \leq g$, for all $n \in \mathbb{N}$. By the definition of $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)$, see (3.8) and (3.6), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
g(n) & =\inf \left\{y \geq 0 \mid \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t_{n}}(y) \geq 0\right\} \\
& =\inf \left\{y \geq 0 \mid m^{\prime}(y)+\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{n}\right)-\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{n}\right)\right) \geq 0\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

As $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t_{n}}(y)$ is strictly increasing in $y$, we obtain that for all $\delta>0$ and $n \in \mathbb{N}$,

$$
m^{\prime}(g(n)-\delta)<-\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{n}\right)+\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{n}\right)\right) \leq m^{\prime}(g(n)+\delta)
$$

Consider the case when $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(t)$ is not left-continuous at $t$, that is when $g<g(\infty)$. Then take $\delta=\frac{g(\infty)-g}{2}>0$, which implies that

$$
g(n)+\delta=g(n)+\frac{g(\infty)-g}{2} \leq \frac{g(\infty)+g}{2}=g(\infty)-\frac{g(\infty)-g}{2}=g(\infty)-\delta
$$

Thus, from (3.11) we derive that

$$
\begin{aligned}
-\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{n}\right)+\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{n}\right)\right) & \leq m^{\prime}(g(n)+\delta) \\
& \leq m^{\prime}(g(\infty)-\delta) \\
& <-\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $\bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(\cdot)$ is continuous and $\bar{F}_{b}(\cdot)$ is left-continuous, it holds that

$$
\begin{aligned}
-\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right) & =\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty}-\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}\left(1-t_{n}\right)+\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\left(t_{n}\right)\right) \\
& <-\lambda \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where the strict inequality follows from (3.12). Thus, we arrived at a contradiction to $g<$ $g(\infty)$, which implies that $\bar{G}_{\lambda, \mu}(\cdot)$ is indeed left-continuous at $t$.

Finally, we establish the optimal quantile function to problem $(\bar{P})$. In particular, the optimal quantile function is given in (3.8) with a particular choice of Lagrange multipliers.

Theorem 3.5 (Optimal quantile function). Let Assumption 3.1 be satisfied and the benchmark fulfils $0<\bar{F}_{b}(t)<+\infty$, for all $t \in(0,1)$. Then there exists a unique quantile function that solves $(\bar{P})$, which is given by

$$
\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)
$$

with $\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)$ defined in (3.8) and the Lagrange multipliers $\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*} \geq 0$ satisfy the slackness conditions

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda^{*}\left(\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}^{*}\right)-x_{0}\right) & =0, \quad \text { and } \\
\mu^{*}\left(\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}^{*}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)-\varepsilon\right) & =0
\end{aligned}
$$

Proof. By Theorems 3.2 and A.1, there exists a pair of multipliers $\lambda^{*}$ and $\mu^{*}$ such that the Karush-Kuhn-Tucker (KKT) conditions hold. Denote by $\bar{F}^{*} \in \mathcal{Q}_{\varepsilon}\left(x_{0}\right)$ the solution satisfying the KKT conditions and recall that $\bar{F}^{*}$ is also the solution to (3.4) with Lagrange multipliers $\left(\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}\right)$. We proceed to show that $\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)$ for all $t \in(0,1)$, where $\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}$ is the solution to (3.8) with Lagrange multipliers $\left(\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}\right)$.

Denote by $\mathcal{I}_{1}:=\left\{t \in(0,1) \mid \bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)<+\infty\right\}$ and by $\mathcal{I}_{2}:=\left\{t \in(0,1) \mid \bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)=+\infty\right\}$. We show by contradiction that $\mathcal{I}_{2}=\emptyset$. For this assume that $\mathcal{I}_{2} \neq \emptyset$. Then from the proof of Proposition 3.3, it holds that $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0} \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}^{*}(y)<0$, where $h_{t}^{*}(\cdot)$ is given in (3.6) with multipliers $\lambda^{*}$ and $\mu^{*}$. Recall that by assumption on the state price density and the benchmark, we have $0<\bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(t), \bar{F}_{b}(t)<+\infty$ for all $t \in(0,1)$. Thus along with the Inada-conditions, we obtain for all $t \in(0,1)$

$$
\lim _{y \rightarrow \infty} \frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}^{*}(y)=\lim _{y \rightarrow \infty}-u^{\prime}(y)+\lambda^{*} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu^{*}\left(\phi^{\prime}(y)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right)>0
$$

Specifically, the strict inequality above holds in all three cases: $\left(\lambda^{*}>0, \mu^{*}>0\right),\left(\lambda^{*}=0, \mu^{*}>\right.$ $0)$ and $\left(\lambda^{*}>0, \mu^{*}=0\right)$. Therefore, by the monotonicity of $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}^{*}(y)$, we conclude that there exists a $y^{\dagger} \in(0, \infty)$ such that $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}^{*}\left(y^{\dagger}\right)=0$, which implies $\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)<+\infty$ for all $t \in(0,1)$. Since we concluded that $\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)$ is a finitely valued function on $(0,1)$, we have $\mathcal{I}_{2}=\emptyset$ and $\mathcal{I}_{1}=(0,1)$. By Proposition 3.3, $\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}$ uniquely minimizes the Lagrangian over the set of functions mapping $(0,1)$ to $[0, \infty)$. Since $\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}$ is a quantile function itself, it also minimize the Lagrangian over the set of quantile functions and we conclude that $\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}}(t)$ for all $t \in(0,1)$.

Next, we show that the optimal quantile function has a simple representation.
Corollary 3.6. Let Assumption 3.1 be satisfied and the benchmark fulfils $0<\bar{F}_{b}(t)<+\infty$, for all $t \in(0,1)$. Then the unique quantile function that solves $(\bar{P})$ has representation

$$
\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\left(m^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(-\lambda^{*} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)+\mu^{*} \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\right)
$$

where $\left(m^{\prime}\right)^{-1}$ is the inverse of $m^{\prime}(y)=-u^{\prime}(y)+\mu^{*} \phi^{\prime}(y)$, and $\lambda^{*}$ and $\mu^{*}$ are given in Theorem 3.5 .

Proof. From the proof of Theorem 3.5, it holds that the optimal quantile function is finite, i.e. $\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*} \cdot \mu^{*}}(t)<+\infty$, for all $t \in(0,1)$. Thus, from Proposition 3.3 we have that for each $t \in(0,1), \bar{G}_{\lambda^{*} \cdot \mu^{*}}(t)$ is the solution to

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial y} h_{t}^{*}(y)=m^{\prime}(y)+\lambda^{*} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)-\mu^{*} \phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)=0
$$

where $h_{t}^{*}(\cdot)$ is given in (3.6) with multipliers $\lambda^{*}$ and $\mu^{*}$. Solving (3.13) for $y$ concludes the proof.

From Theorems 3.2 and 3.5 we observe that there are three possible cases for the optimal quantile function:
i) Both constraints are binding, i.e., $\lambda^{*}, \mu^{*}>0$. Then, $\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*} \cdot \mu^{*}}(t)$ and

$$
\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}^{*}\right)=x_{0} \quad \text { and } \quad \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}^{*}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)=\varepsilon
$$

ii) Only the budget constraint is binding, i.e., $\lambda^{*}>0$ and $\mu^{*}=0$. Then, $\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{\lambda^{*}, 0}(t)$ and

$$
\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}^{*}\right)=x_{0}
$$

iii) Only the BW constraint is binding, i.e., $\lambda^{*}=0$ and $\mu^{*}>0$. Then, $\bar{F}^{*}(t)=\bar{G}_{0, \mu^{*}}(t)$ and

$$
\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}^{*}, \bar{F}_{b}\right)=\varepsilon
$$

4. Examples. In this section we illustrate the theoretical results. We derive optimal payoffs and evaluate how these depend on the choice of the BW divergence, that is, on how investors reward positive deviations and penalize negative ones. We first layout the market model and then discuss how to choose the tolerance level $\varepsilon$ and the Bregman generating function $\phi$.
4.1. Market model. We provide examples within the Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM) market framework. In this market, there is a stock $\left(S_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ and a risk-free asset $\left(B_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ satisfying the stochastic differential equations

$$
\mathrm{d} S_{t}=\mu_{s} S_{t} \mathrm{~d} t+\sigma_{s} S_{t} \mathrm{~d} W_{t}, \quad \text { and } \quad \mathrm{d} B_{t}=r B_{t}
$$

respectively, where $\left(W_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ is a standard Brownian motion, and the stock has drift $\mu_{s} \in \mathbb{R}$ and instantaneous volatility $\sigma_{s}>0$. Under the no-arbitrage condition the state price density $\varphi_{T}$ is uniquely given by

$$
\varphi_{T}=e^{-\left(r+\frac{1}{2} \theta^{2}\right) T-\theta W_{T}}
$$

in which $\theta=\frac{\mu_{s}-r}{\sigma_{s}}$. Hence, $\varphi_{T}$ follows a log-normal distribution with mean $\mu_{\varphi}:=-\left(r+\frac{1}{2} \theta^{2}\right) T$ and standard deviation $\sigma_{\varphi}:=\theta \sqrt{T}$, denoted as $\varphi_{T} \sim \operatorname{LN}\left(\mu_{\varphi}, \sigma_{\varphi}^{2}\right)$. Its cdf and quantile function are

$$
F_{\varphi_{T}}(x)=\Phi\left(\frac{\ln x-\mu_{\varphi}}{\sigma_{\varphi}}\right) \quad \text { and } \quad \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(t)=e^{\mu_{\varphi}+\sigma_{\varphi} \bar{\Phi}(t)}
$$

where $\Phi(\cdot)$ and $\hat{\Phi}(\cdot)$ are the cdf and quantile function of the standard normal distribution, respectively.

In all our numerical experiments, we assume the following parameters for the market model

$$
T=5, \quad r=0, \quad \mu_{s}=0.05, \quad \sigma_{s}=0.1, \quad \text { and } \quad S_{0}=1
$$

Furthermore, we assume that the investor makes their choices using a Constant Relative Risk Aversion (CRRA) utility function

$$
u(x)= \begin{cases}\frac{x^{1-\gamma}-1}{1-\gamma} & \gamma \geq 0, \gamma \neq 1 \\ \ln x & \gamma=1\end{cases}
$$

in which the parameter $\gamma$ reflects their degree of risk aversion. In the numerical experiments we choose the parameter values $\gamma=1$ and $\gamma=1.5$. Moreover, without any loss of generality, we assume that the investor has a budget $x_{0}=1$.
4.2. Choice of tolerance level $\varepsilon$. When determining their optimal payoff as a solution to problem $(\mathrm{P})$, the investor needs to choose the benchmark quantile function $\bar{F}_{b}$, the tolerance level $\varepsilon$, and the Bregman generating function $\phi$ that determines how deviations from the benchmark $\bar{F}_{b}$ are assessed.

To this regard, we consider the smallest BW distance $\varepsilon_{\min }$ for which problem $(\bar{P})$ is welldefined in that any $\varepsilon$ choice with $\varepsilon>\varepsilon_{\min }$ implies that Assumption 3.1 is satisfied and thus a solution to $(\bar{P})$ exists. Specifically, we define $\varepsilon_{\min }$ as

$$
\varepsilon_{\min }:=\min _{\tilde{G} \in \mathcal{Q}} \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\tilde{G}, \bar{F}_{b}\right), \quad \text { s.t. } \quad \mathfrak{c}(\tilde{G}) \leq x_{0}
$$

Note that in applications it is often reasonable that the initial budget $x_{0}$ satisfies $x_{0}=\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{0}\right)$, which implies that $\varepsilon_{\min }=0$, i.e., the investor can choose any $\varepsilon>0$ as tolerance level for deviations from the benchmark and $(\bar{P})$ is still well-posed. The following proposition provides for any given budget $x_{0}$ and benchmark $\bar{F}_{b}$ the expression for $\varepsilon_{\min }$.

Proposition 4.1. For a budget $x_{0}$ and a benchmark $\bar{F}_{b}$, the minimal $B W$ distance $\varepsilon_{\min }$ is given by

$$
\varepsilon_{\min }= \begin{cases}0 & \text { if } \quad \mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\right) \leq x_{0} \\ \mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\tilde{G}^{*}, \bar{F}_{b}\right) & \text { if } \quad \mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\right)>x_{0}\end{cases}
$$

where

$$
\tilde{G}^{*}(t):=\left(\phi^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{0}(t)-\eta^{*} \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t)\right)\right)
$$

and $\eta^{*}>0$ is the unique solution to $\mathfrak{c}\left(\tilde{G}^{*}\right)=x_{0}$.

Proof. If $\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\right) \leq x_{0}$, then $\varepsilon_{\min }=0$. To see this note that the Bregman divergence $B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)$ is zero, if and only if $z_{1}=z_{2}$, thus $\mathscr{B}_{\phi}(\bar{G}, \bar{F})=0$ if and only if $\bar{G}(u)=\bar{F}(u)$ for all $u \in(0,1)$.

For the second case, assume that $\mathfrak{c}\left(\bar{F}_{b}\right)>x_{0}$. Then the associated Lagrangian to (4.1) with Lagrange multiplier $\eta \geq 0$ is

$$
\int_{0}^{1} \phi(\bar{G}(t))-\phi\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right)\left(\bar{G}(t)-\bar{F}_{b}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t+\eta\left(\int_{0}^{1} \bar{G}(t) \bar{F}_{\varphi_{T}}(1-t) \mathrm{d} t-x_{0}\right)
$$

The remainder of the proof follows using similar arguments as in Propositions 3.3, 3.4, and Theorem 3.5.

For a given tolerance level $\varepsilon$, we observe from Figure 1 that the Bregman divergence between two points vary significantly for different $\phi$. Therefore, we propose to make $\varepsilon$ dependent on the choice of $\phi$. To this end, in a similar spirit to Bernard et al. (2024b), the investor considers a series of strategies that they deem acceptable, and then select the tolerance level $\varepsilon$ as the maximum of the divergences of the acceptable strategies with the benchmark.
4.3. Choice of Bregman generator $\phi$. With the BW divergence, an investor can penalize underperformance and outperformance relative to the benchmark asymmetrically. Moreover, as investors may not want to penalize gains when measured relative to the terminal wealth of the benchmark, see e.g., Harlow (1991) and Klebaner et al. (2017), we introduce a family of Bregman generators who assess deviations in relation to a wealth threshold $\alpha \in[0, \infty)$.

Definition 4.2 (Bregman divergence with threshold $\alpha$ ). Let $\phi: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex and continuously differentiable Bregman generator. For a given threshold $\alpha$, we define the Bregman generator $\tilde{\phi}(\cdot ; \alpha)$ associated with $\phi$ as

$$
\tilde{\phi}(x ; \alpha)=\phi(x) \mathbb{I}_{\{x \leq \alpha\}}+\left(\phi^{\prime}(\alpha)(x-\alpha)+\phi(\alpha)\right) \mathbb{I}_{\{x>\alpha\}}
$$

where $\mathbb{I}_{\{\cdot\}}$ denotes the indicator function. Then the Bregman divergence with generator $\tilde{\phi}(\cdot ; \alpha)$ becomes

$$
\begin{aligned}
B_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha\right)= & B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right) \mathbb{I}_{\left\{z_{1}, z_{2} \leq \alpha\right\}}+B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, \alpha\right) \mathbb{I}_{\left\{z_{1} \leq \alpha<z_{2}\right\}} \\
& +\left\{B_{\phi}\left(\alpha, z_{2}\right)+\left(\phi^{\prime}(\alpha)-\phi^{\prime}\left(z_{2}\right)\right)\left(z_{1}-\alpha\right)\right\} \mathbb{I}_{\left\{z_{2} \leq \alpha<z_{1}\right\}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that $\tilde{\phi}$ is continuously differentiable and convex, thus all relevant results of problem (P) apply to the Bregman divergence with threshold $\alpha$.

We observe that if $z_{1}, z_{2} \leq \alpha$, then $B_{\tilde{\phi}}$ reduces to the Bregman divergence with $\phi$ and if $z_{1}, z_{2}>\alpha$, then $B_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha\right)=0$, meaning that the Bregman divergence no longer accounts for the distance between points that both exceed the threshold $\alpha$. If $z_{1} \leq \alpha<z_{2}$, the divergence equals $B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, \alpha\right)$, that is only deviation of $z_{1}$ to the reference point $\alpha$ are taken into account, independent of the value of $z_{2}$. Moreover, due to the asymmetry of the Bregman divergence, if $z_{2} \leq \alpha<z_{1}$, the penalization is not only $B_{\phi}\left(\alpha, z_{2}\right)$ but also via the derivative of $\phi$. The Bregman divergence with threshold $\alpha$ thus combines the tractability of Bregman divergence with the ability to measure downside risk relative to the wealth threshold $\alpha$ and

to moreover penalize underperformance relative to the benchmark. To gain a deeper understanding of the role of the threshold $\alpha$, Proposition 4.3 establishes the monotonicity and limit properties of $\mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2} ; \alpha\right)$ with respect to $\alpha$. Its proof is relegated to Appendix B.

Proposition 4.3. For $\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2} \in \mathcal{Q}$, the function $\alpha \mapsto \mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2} ; \alpha\right)$ is non-decreasing. Moreover, it holds that

$$
\lim _{\alpha \rightarrow 0^{+}} \mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2} ; \alpha\right)=0, \quad \text { and } \quad \lim _{\alpha \rightarrow \infty} \mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2} ; \alpha\right)=\mathscr{B}_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2}\right)
$$

The key emphasis of the divergence $\mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}, \bar{F}_{2} ; \alpha\right)$ is when $\bar{F}_{1}$ and $\bar{F}_{2}$ do not simultaneously exceed the threshold $\alpha$. Specifically, for $t \in(0,1)$, if both $\bar{F}_{1}(t)$ and $\bar{F}_{2}(t)$ are less than $\alpha$, then $B_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t), \bar{F}_{2}(t) ; \alpha\right)=B_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t), \bar{F}_{2}(t)\right)$, indicating that the divergence is measured using the Bregman divergence with $\phi$. However, if $\bar{F}_{1}(t)$ and $\bar{F}_{2}(t)$ lie on opposite sides of $\alpha$, then $B_{\tilde{\phi}}\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t), \bar{F}_{2}(t) ; \alpha\right) \leq B_{\phi}\left(\bar{F}_{1}(t), \bar{F}_{2}(t)\right)$, thereby penalizing less than with $B_{\phi}$, and if both $\bar{F}_{1}(t)$ and $\bar{F}_{2}(t)$ are larger than the wealth threshold $\alpha$ the divergence is zero.

Alternatively, we can view $\mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}$ as a function of $\alpha$. If $\alpha=0$, the investor's problem (P) reduces to the case without a divergence constraint, that is the classical Merton problem. As $\alpha$ increases to infinity, $\mathscr{B}_{\tilde{\phi}}$ converges to the BW divergence with $\phi$. Therefore, $\alpha$ can be regarded as a weighting parameter that interpolates between these two extreme cases.

In the numerical examples below, we use the following two convex functions as Bregman generators

$$
\phi_{1}(x)=x^{2} \quad \text { and } \quad \phi_{2}(x)=x \ln x, \quad \text { for } \quad x>0
$$

The choice $\phi_{1}$ corresponds to the 2-Wasserstein distance where positive and negative deviations from the benchmark quantiles are penalized equally. By contrast, under $\phi_{2}$ deviations are penalized in an asymmetric manner in that negative deviations (underperforming the benchmark) receive more weight than positive ones (outperforming the benchmark). Further, note that the convexity of $\phi_{2}$ becomes less strong when $x$ increases, thus underperforming the benchmark is penalised significantly more. We further use these two convex functions as generators for the Bregman divergence with given threshold $\alpha$, which then become

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{\phi}_{1}(x ; \alpha)=x^{2} \mathbb{I}_{\{x \leq \alpha\}}+2 \alpha\left(x-\frac{\alpha}{2}\right) \mathbb{I}_{\{x>\alpha\}} \\
& \tilde{\phi}_{2}(x ; \alpha)=x \ln x \mathbb{I}_{\{x \leq \alpha\}}+((\ln \alpha+1) x-\alpha) \mathbb{I}_{\{x>\alpha\}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that both generators are linear in $x$ on $(\alpha, \infty)$.
4.4. Example 1: Optimal payoff when the benchmark is a constant. We study optimal payoff choice for an investor who aims to maximize his expected utility under the constraint that their terminal wealth does not diverge too much from the terminal wealth when pursuing an investment bearing a fixed rate of return $\kappa>0$. That is, we assume in problem (P) that the benchmark's quantile function is $\bar{F}_{b} \equiv e^{\kappa T}$. This situation corresponds to the case of pension fund managers whose performance and solvency position might be assessed with reference to such a benchmark. For instance, under a fair value approach, the supervisory authorities may require that $\bar{F}_{b} \equiv e^{\kappa T}$, where $\kappa$ is equal to the risk free rate $r$.

In order to determine the appropriate tolerance level $\varepsilon$, the investor considers three investment strategies that he deems acceptable (although not necessarily optimal). For each of these strategies, the investor calculates their BW divergence to the benchmark's and defines $\varepsilon$ as the maximum among them (one for each of the Bregman generator $\phi$ we study). The three acceptable strategies are as follows:

Strategy 1: The constant mix strategy is a strategy where one maintains, through continuous rebalancing, a portfolio which during the entire investment period $[0, T]$ keeps the proportions invested in the riskless asset respectively in the stock constant. We consider $82.5 \%$ invested in the risk-free asset and the remaining proportion of $17.5 \%$ is invested in stock, in which case, the quantile function of the terminal wealth is

$$
\bar{F}_{T}(u)=e^{\mu_{1}+\sigma_{1} \hat{\Phi}(u)}, \quad u \in(0,1)
$$

where $\mu_{1}:=\left(r+\left(\mu_{s}-r\right) 0.175-\frac{1}{2} 0.175^{2} \sigma_{s}^{2}\right) T$ and $\sigma_{1}:=0.175 \sigma_{s} \sqrt{T}$.
Strategy 2: For this strategy one invests at $t=0$ a proportion of the initial wealth in the risk-free asset and the remaining proportion in the stock. This is a buy and hold strategy, meaning that during $(0, T]$ there are no trades, thus the relative exposures to the risk-free asset and to the stock evolves over time. We consider $85 \%$ of the initial wealth invested in the risk-free asset and the remaining proportion of $15 \%$ is invested in stock. The terminal wealth's quantile function is

$$
\bar{F}_{T}(u)=\left(0.15 e^{\mu_{2}+\sigma_{2} \hat{\Phi}(u)}+0.85 e^{r T}\right), \quad u \in(0,1)
$$

where $\mu_{2}:=\left(\mu_{s}-\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{s}^{2}\right) T$ and $\sigma_{2}:=\sigma_{s} \sqrt{T}$.
Strategy 3: This strategy yields a so-called digital payoff $Y_{T}$ on the stock $S_{T}$, given by

$$
Y_{T}=0.9 \mathbb{I}_{\left\{S_{T} \leq c\right\}}+\frac{1}{0.95}\left(e^{r T}-0.045\right) \mathbb{I}_{\left\{S_{T}>c\right\}}
$$

where $c>0$ is such that $\mathbb{Q}\left(S_{T}<c\right)=0.05$. Note that the cost of $Y_{T}$ is indeed equal to $x_{0}=1$. Its quantile function is given as

$$
\bar{F}_{T}(u)=0.9 \mathbb{I}_{\left\{u \leq \alpha_{c}\right\}}+\frac{1}{0.95}\left(e^{r T}-0.045\right) \mathbb{I}_{\left\{u>\alpha_{c}\right\}}, \quad u \in(0,1)
$$

where $\alpha_{c}:=\mathbb{P}\left(S_{T}<c\right)$.

5. Concluding remarks. In this paper, we deal with optimal payoff choice for an expected utility maximizer who aims to stay close to a benchmark, but considers asymmetry in that positive deviations are measured differently than negative ones. Doing so has significant impact on the payoff choice. By acknowledging and accounting for the asymmetric preferences of investors, financial professionals can design products and strategies that better align with their clients' preferences and risk tolerances.

Appendix A. Convex Optimization in Banach Spaces. In this appendix, we collect auxiliary results on convex optimisation problems.

Theorem A. 1 (Barbu and Precupanu (2012)). Consider $L$ as a real linear space, and let $f: L \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function. Define the feasible set $\mathcal{F}_{L}$ as follows:

$$
\mathcal{F}_{L}:=\left\{x \in L \mid g_{i}(x) \leq 0 \forall i=1, \ldots, n\right\}
$$

where $g_{i}$ and $r_{i}$ are real-valued functions on $L$, convex or affine. Assume that $\mathcal{F}_{L}$ is nonempty and consider the optimization problem

$$
\min \left\{f(x) \mid x \in \mathcal{F}_{L}\right\}
$$

If $x^{*} \in \mathcal{F}_{L}$ is an solution to this problem, i.e.,

$$
f\left(x^{*}\right)=\min \left\{f(x) \mid x \in \mathcal{F}_{L}\right\}
$$

then there exist $n+1$ real numbers $\nu^{*}, \lambda_{1}^{*}, \ldots, \lambda_{n}^{*}$ satisfying:

1. $\nu^{*} \geq 0$, and $\lambda_{i}^{*} \geq 0$ for all $i=1, \ldots, n$;
2. $\nu^{*} f\left(x^{*}\right) \leq \nu^{*} f(x)+\sum_{i=1}^{n} \lambda_{i}^{*} g_{i}(x)$ for all $x \in \mathcal{F}_{L}$;
3. $\lambda_{i}^{*} g_{i}\left(x^{*}\right)=0$ for all $i=1, \ldots, n$.

Definition A. 2 (Lagrangian function). For the above convex optimization problem, define its Lagrangian function as

$$
\mathcal{L}(x, \lambda, \mu)=f(x)+\sum_{i=1}^{n} \lambda_{i} g_{i}(x)
$$

for all $(x, \lambda) \in L \times \mathbb{R}_{+}^{n}$.
Theorem A. 1 provides the necessary conditions for a solution to exist. With certain additional assumptions, we can demonstrate that these conditions are also sufficient.

Definition A. 3 (Slater condition). An optimization problem satisfies the Slater condition if there exists a point $x_{0} \in \mathcal{F}_{L}$ such that

$$
g_{i}\left(x_{0}\right)<0 \quad \forall i=1, \ldots, n
$$

Specifically, if $g_{k}$ is an affine constraint, the above condition can be relaxed to a non-strict inequality, i.e., $g_{k}\left(x_{0}\right) \leq 0$, see Boyd and Vandenberghe (2004).

Theorem A. 4 (Barbu and Precupanu (2012)). Under the assumptions of Theorem A.1, if we additionally assume that the Slater condition holds, then the necessary conditions of Theorem A. 1 become sufficient for optimality, which implies $\nu^{*}>0$. Furthermore, it is sufficient to optimize the Lagrangian function $\mathcal{L}\left(x, \lambda^{*}\right)$ with respect to $x$ over $L$.

Appendix B. Proof of Proposition 4.3. This appendix is devoted to additional proofs not provided in the main body of the paper.

Proof. We first prove that $\alpha \mapsto B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha\right)$ is non-decreasing for fixed non-negative $z_{1}$ and $z_{2}$. First, let $\alpha_{1} \leq z_{1} \leq \alpha_{2} \leq z_{2} \leq \alpha_{3}$, then we prove that

$$
B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{1}\right) \leq B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2}\right) \leq B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{3}\right)
$$

From (4.2), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{1}\right)=0 \\
& B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2}\right)=\phi\left(z_{1}\right)-\phi\left(\alpha_{2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2}\right)\left(z_{1}-\alpha_{2}\right) \\
& B_{\dot{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{3}\right)=\phi\left(z_{1}\right)-\phi\left(z_{2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(z_{2}\right)\left(z_{1}-z_{2}\right)=B_{\phi}\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that only $B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2}\right)$ depends on the threshold $\alpha$. Let $\alpha_{2,1}, \alpha_{2,2} \in\left[z_{1}, z_{2}\right]$, with $\alpha_{2,1} \leq \alpha_{2,2}$. Then using in the second equation the Mean Value Theorem with $\xi \in\left[\alpha_{2,1}, \alpha_{2,2}\right]$, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
& B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2,2}\right)-B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2,1}\right) \\
= & -\phi\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)+\phi\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)\left(z_{1}-\alpha_{2,2}\right)+\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)\left(z_{1}-\alpha_{2,1}\right) \\
= & -\phi^{\prime}(\xi)\left(\alpha_{2,2}-\alpha_{2,1}\right)-\left(\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)\right) z_{1}+\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right) \alpha_{2,2}-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right) \alpha_{2,1} \\
= & \left(\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}(\xi)\right) \alpha_{2,2}-\left(\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)\right) z_{1}+\left(\phi^{\prime}(\xi)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)\right) \alpha_{2,1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $\phi^{\prime}(\cdot)$ is non-decreasing, we have $\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}(\xi) \geq \phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,2}\right)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)$. Combing with $\alpha_{2,2} \geq z_{1}$ and that $\alpha_{2,1} \geq 0$, we get

$$
B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2,2}\right)-B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2,1}\right) \geq\left(\phi^{\prime}(\xi)-\phi^{\prime}\left(\alpha_{2,1}\right)\right) \alpha_{2,1} \geq 0
$$

which implies that $\alpha_{2} \mapsto B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2}\right)$ is non-decreasing on $\left[z_{1}, z_{2}\right]$. Thus, we obtain

$$
B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{1}\right)=B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; z_{1}\right) \leq B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{2}\right) \leq B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; z_{2}\right)=B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha_{3}\right)
$$

Similarly, when $z_{1}>z_{2}$, we can prove that the inequalities (B.1) and (B.2) hold, i.e., $\alpha \mapsto$ $B_{\hat{\phi}}\left(z_{1}, z_{2} ; \alpha\right)$ is non-decreasing. Thus, we conclude that $\alpha \mapsto \mathscr{B}_{\hat{\phi}}\left(\hat{F}_{1}, \hat{F}_{2} ; \alpha\right)$ is non-decreasing. Finally, taking the limit in $\alpha$, we obtain (4.3).

abstract:
We study optimal payoff choice for an expected utility maximizer under the
constraint that their payoff is not allowed to deviate ``too much'' from a
given benchmark. We solve this problem when the deviation is assessed via a
Bregman-Wasserstein (BW) divergence, generated by a convex function $\phi$.
Unlike the Wasserstein distance (i.e., when $\phi(x)=x^2$). The inherent
asymmetry of the BW divergence makes it possible to penalize positive
deviations different than negative ones. As a main contribution, we provide the
optimal payoff in this setting. Numerical examples illustrate that the choice
of $\phi$ allow to better align the payoff choice with the objectives of
investors.
